WEBVTT

01:00.000 --> 01:03.000
Room.237.2012.720p.BluRay.x264.YIFY

01:06.984 --> 01:11.279
- The poster
that came out in Europe,

01:11.280 --> 01:12.497
at least in England,
I believe,

01:12.498 --> 01:18.160
before the movie was released
in Europe said,

01:18.161 --> 01:22.331
"The wave of terror
that swept across America."

01:22.332 --> 01:25.506
And Kubrick controlled
the posters very carefully.

01:25.507 --> 01:28.671
Now,
it made you do a double take.

01:28.672 --> 01:30.089
I remember seeing it in Europe.

01:30.090 --> 01:31.637
I was the Rome Bureau Chief
at the time for ABC News.

01:31.638 --> 01:33.009
And I remember looking at it.

01:33.010 --> 01:34.512
It said, "The wave of terror
that swept across America."

01:34.513 --> 01:36.512
What's he talking about?

01:36.513 --> 01:41.267
And you'd sort of think
that he was talking about

01:41.268 --> 01:43.362
the impact
of the book The Shining.

01:43.363 --> 01:44.604
Maybe.

01:44.605 --> 01:47.324
The impact of the movie
that had just opened over there?

01:47.325 --> 01:48.316
Maybe.

01:48.317 --> 01:49.859
It didn't quite fit.

01:49.860 --> 01:51.658
The wave of terror
that swept across America

01:51.659 --> 01:53.906
from Portland, Maine,
to Portland, Oregon,

01:53.907 --> 01:56.704
was the genocidal armies
and the white men with their ax

01:56.705 --> 02:00.786
clearing it all and bringing in
extractive industries,

02:00.787 --> 02:02.288
among many other good things
as well.

02:02.289 --> 02:04.542
But that was the wave of terror
that swept across America,

02:04.543 --> 02:08.216
terrifying, of course,
the American Indians.

02:31.234 --> 02:34.281
- I went in to see this movie in
Leicester Square Movie Theater,

02:34.282 --> 02:36.619
right near
Leicester Square in London.

02:36.620 --> 02:38.454
And I remember it
quite clearly from...

02:38.455 --> 02:40.496
I can even remember the seats
we were sitting in.

02:40.497 --> 02:42.872
If I went back to that theater,
I could point them to you,

02:42.873 --> 02:47.500
sort of near the back
and over to the left.

02:47.501 --> 02:51.381
From the moment of the opening
astonishing helicopter shot,

02:51.382 --> 02:53.255
I was terrified.

02:53.256 --> 02:54.882
I had no idea what was coming.

02:54.883 --> 02:56.726
I remember sort of sitting
on the front edge

02:56.727 --> 03:01.263
of my theater seat there
to keep from falling off.

03:01.264 --> 03:05.144
And I remember gripping my
belt buckle with my left hand,

03:05.145 --> 03:06.435
I think it was...

03:06.436 --> 03:09.440
yes, my left hand,
sort of to keep from falling off

03:09.441 --> 03:14.443
the edge of the seat
and to try to control my terror

03:14.444 --> 03:15.739
as I watched this movie.

03:15.740 --> 03:17.113
I had no idea what was coming.

03:17.114 --> 03:18.327
I hadn't read the book.

03:18.328 --> 03:20.746
I had barely seen
any of the posters.

03:20.747 --> 03:25.871
And I remember that I was
stunned when the movie was over.

03:25.872 --> 03:28.624
We left the theater, went in...

03:28.625 --> 03:30.468
down into
our underground car park

03:30.469 --> 03:34.004
to get into the car to leave.

03:34.005 --> 03:36.804
And as we were driving up
out of the car park,

03:36.805 --> 03:39.468
I was sitting
in the back left seat.

03:39.469 --> 03:41.554
I was thinking, "What was that?
What was that?

03:41.555 --> 03:42.555
"What was it?
What was it?

03:42.556 --> 03:43.597
What was it?"

03:43.598 --> 03:47.435
And I think
my visual imagination

03:47.436 --> 03:49.109
looked at that
Calumet baking powder can,

03:49.110 --> 03:50.651
the one right behind
Hallorann's head

03:50.652 --> 03:52.898
when he was talking to Danny.

03:52.899 --> 03:54.196
I knew what "calumet" meant.

03:54.197 --> 03:56.694
It meant "peace pipe."

03:56.695 --> 04:01.157
And I thought to myself,
"peace pipe, Indians.

04:01.158 --> 04:02.450
"Oh, my goodness,

04:02.451 --> 04:04.499
they're all over the place
in that movie."

04:11.209 --> 04:13.928
- The loser
has to keep America clean.

04:19.091 --> 04:21.635
- And I suddenly
said to my friends,

04:21.636 --> 04:23.100
"That movie
was about the genocide

04:23.101 --> 04:24.560
of the American Indians."

04:24.561 --> 04:26.727
And they said,
"What are you talking about?"

04:26.728 --> 04:28.064
And I started explaining it,

04:28.065 --> 04:30.811
because I'd noticed
the Calumet baking soda can.

04:30.812 --> 04:32.860
In the first... the first time
we seen one,

04:32.861 --> 04:36.108
it's a single
baking powder can straight on.

04:36.109 --> 04:37.985
And you can see the whole word,
"Calumet,"

04:37.986 --> 04:40.196
so there's no duplicity,

04:40.197 --> 04:41.915
like the little girls
represent later.

04:41.916 --> 04:43.824
This is an honest truth,

04:43.825 --> 04:45.910
an honest peace pipe
between them.

04:45.911 --> 04:47.629
The other time we see
the Calumet baking powder cans

04:47.630 --> 04:49.874
is when they're
very carefully placed

04:49.875 --> 04:53.673
behind Jack Nicholson's head
when he's talking to Grady.

04:58.381 --> 05:00.634
- No need to rub it in,
Mr. Grady.

05:02.260 --> 05:06.058
I'll deal with that situation
as soon as I get out of here.

05:06.059 --> 05:08.808
- There's about six
or seven of them stacked up,

05:08.809 --> 05:10.398
and they're
all turned different ways,

05:10.399 --> 05:12.564
and you can't read
any one of them completely.

05:12.565 --> 05:15.657
It's... I've always interpreted
those as being broken,

05:15.658 --> 05:18.067
dishonest peace pipe treaties.

05:18.068 --> 05:21.072
They're not... these two guys,
Grady and Jack,

05:21.073 --> 05:24.156
are not being honest
with each other.

05:24.157 --> 05:26.909
Grady is trying to get Jack
to go kill his family

05:26.910 --> 05:28.249
and commit genocide,

05:28.250 --> 05:29.747
in the larger sense
of the movie.

05:29.748 --> 05:32.039
You know, I mean,
Kubrick often,

05:32.040 --> 05:35.376
in many of his movies,

05:35.377 --> 05:37.048
he will end them
with a puzzle

05:37.049 --> 05:39.764
so that he forces you to go out
of the theater saying,

05:39.765 --> 05:41.632
"What was that about?"

05:41.633 --> 05:44.718
And he would put things
in the scenes

05:44.719 --> 05:46.266
that he knows will be,
among other things,

05:46.267 --> 05:49.312
like confirmers when people
start to try to figure out

05:49.313 --> 05:51.100
what the movie is about.

05:51.101 --> 05:53.894
And we know he took
this kind of care.

05:53.895 --> 05:55.896
There's a photograph
in one of the books

05:55.897 --> 05:57.523
that actually shows Kubrick

05:57.524 --> 05:59.367
carefully arranging
objects on the shelves

05:59.368 --> 06:01.861
in that dry goods room.

06:01.862 --> 06:03.487
I thought afterwards,

06:03.488 --> 06:06.617
"How come I saw this and
a lot of other people didn't?"

06:06.618 --> 06:08.409
And I've thought about it.

06:08.410 --> 06:09.749
It's a combination of factors.

06:09.750 --> 06:12.588
First, I grew up in Chicago
and, therefore,

06:12.589 --> 06:14.957
just north
of the Calumet Harbor

06:14.958 --> 06:19.420
and spent summers up
in the sand dunes of Michigan,

06:19.421 --> 06:21.139
around on the other side
of Lake Michigan.

06:21.140 --> 06:23.302
My father
took me and my sister out

06:23.303 --> 06:25.885
to collect little bits
of Indian pottery.

06:25.886 --> 06:27.308
I'd already...
I'd already covered,

06:27.309 --> 06:28.846
at that point in 1980,

06:28.847 --> 06:31.807
five years
of the Lebanese civil war.

06:31.808 --> 06:34.186
I was, at that point,
covering John Paul ll.

06:34.187 --> 06:35.686
I was the Rome Bureau Chief.

06:35.687 --> 06:38.609
And listening
to what he was saying about...

06:38.610 --> 06:41.235
because he had experienced
the Holocaust at its epicenter

06:41.236 --> 06:43.360
and also other horrors.

06:43.361 --> 06:46.405
And so all of those factors

06:46.406 --> 06:48.532
were very much alive in my mind

06:48.533 --> 06:50.326
when we went
to see The Shining,

06:50.327 --> 06:52.705
which I just thought was going
to be some kind of horror movie

06:52.706 --> 06:53.704
by this great moviemaker.

06:53.705 --> 06:58.626
And all of those coming together
along with the little key,

06:58.627 --> 07:01.503
the Calumet baking soda can,

07:01.504 --> 07:04.173
is why I just happened
to tune to it

07:04.174 --> 07:08.969
as we were driving up out of
that underground parking garage

07:08.970 --> 07:10.187
just off Leicester Square.

07:13.183 --> 07:16.733
- I first saw the movie in 1980
when it first came out

07:16.734 --> 07:19.605
and saw it probably two times.

07:19.606 --> 07:21.777
I can say that I remembered
the skier poster.

07:21.778 --> 07:24.198
That is one thing
that really stuck with me.

07:24.199 --> 07:26.028
And the window.

07:26.029 --> 07:27.368
The window in the office,

07:27.369 --> 07:29.537
that's another thing
that really stuck with me.

07:31.785 --> 07:34.582
I remember, you know,
in the newspapers afterwards,

07:34.583 --> 07:35.749
people being disappointed.

07:35.750 --> 07:37.498
And I remember people
that I knew,

07:37.499 --> 07:39.092
yes, in dialogue afterwards,

07:39.093 --> 07:42.920
being disappointed that it was
not more a horror film.

07:42.921 --> 07:47.257
Well, no Kubrick film's
really just a regular movie.

07:47.258 --> 07:49.093
I understood that from,

07:49.094 --> 07:51.893
well, when I was 10 years old
and I first saw 2001.

07:51.894 --> 07:52.888
I walked away.

07:52.889 --> 07:54.434
I thought, "This is a film

07:54.435 --> 07:56.480
that's supposed
to make me think."

07:58.770 --> 08:02.231
- I had my first
religious experience

08:02.232 --> 08:07.778
seeing the film
2001: A Space Odyssey in 1968.

08:07.779 --> 08:14.243
I was a smart kid
and liked art,

08:14.244 --> 08:16.578
but I really
did not like movies

08:16.579 --> 08:20.249
and thought that they
were really a substandard art.

08:20.250 --> 08:21.752
And, you know, films like

08:21.753 --> 08:24.795
My Fair Lady
and Doctor Dolittle were out.

08:24.796 --> 08:29.925
And it was a rather pathetic
time in the '60s for films.

08:29.926 --> 08:32.428
And my girlfriend,
she pulled up

08:32.429 --> 08:36.097
and told me that she'd
seen a movie the night before

08:36.099 --> 08:38.100
and she wanted to see it again.

08:38.101 --> 08:40.945
So she took me to the theater,
the Cinerama Dome,

08:40.946 --> 08:42.479
and I watched it.

08:42.480 --> 08:46.817
And I had never in my life
envisioned that a movie

08:46.818 --> 08:49.278
could do what this movie
was doing.

08:49.279 --> 08:52.123
And it was showing me things
that I had never seen,

08:52.124 --> 08:54.783
and it was
intellectually challenging.

08:54.784 --> 08:59.621
And it was an artistic
masterpiece in every way,

08:59.622 --> 09:04.126
from the soundtrack to
the visuals to the story line.

09:04.127 --> 09:07.051
And when the movie ended,
I couldn't get out of my seat.

09:07.052 --> 09:09.465
I was frozen in the seat,

09:09.466 --> 09:13.093
completely paralyzed
by what I'd just witnessed.

09:13.094 --> 09:16.722
And the usher actually
had to come and get me out.

09:16.723 --> 09:19.433
And I was the last person,
me and her.

09:19.434 --> 09:21.852
And I staggered
out of the theater

09:21.853 --> 09:24.563
completely changed
as a human being

09:24.564 --> 09:25.816
and decided at that moment

09:25.817 --> 09:27.816
that the only thing
that I wanted to do

09:27.817 --> 09:29.485
for the rest of my life

09:29.486 --> 09:32.988
was to make films
in one fashion or another.

09:32.989 --> 09:35.115
And so I have done that.

09:35.116 --> 09:40.037
So I owe Stanley Kubrick and
his film 2001: A Space Odyssey

09:40.038 --> 09:44.708
everything for everything that
I have become in my life, so...

10:02.018 --> 10:03.861
- I saw a number
of Kubrick films

10:03.862 --> 10:06.980
before I had
an academic interest in him.

10:06.981 --> 10:11.527
And then I went to see
The Shining in 1980.

10:11.528 --> 10:14.368
And frankly,
I didn't think that much of it.

10:14.369 --> 10:16.867
I thought the other
Kubrick films that I'd seen

10:16.868 --> 10:19.868
were far superior.

10:19.869 --> 10:24.581
But as I thought
about the film afterwards...

10:24.582 --> 10:26.753
and even when
I wasn't thinking about it...

10:26.754 --> 10:29.004
there were things
that bothered me about it.

10:29.005 --> 10:32.214
It seemed
as if I had missed something.

10:32.215 --> 10:35.384
And so I went back
to see it again.

10:35.385 --> 10:39.054
And I began to see
patterns and details

10:39.055 --> 10:42.057
that I hadn't noticed before.

10:42.058 --> 10:46.395
And so I kept watching the film
again and again and again.

10:46.396 --> 10:49.356
And since
I'm trained as an historian

10:49.357 --> 10:51.817
and my special expertise

10:51.818 --> 10:56.697
is in the history of Germany
and Nazi Germany in particular,

10:56.698 --> 10:58.291
I became
more and more convinced

10:58.292 --> 11:02.077
that there is,
in this film,

11:02.078 --> 11:06.049
a deeply laid subtext
that takes on The Holocaust.

11:07.917 --> 11:12.838
I think
it probably was the typewriter,

11:12.839 --> 11:16.925
which was a German brand,
which might seem arbitrary,

11:16.926 --> 11:20.387
but by that time,
I knew enough about Kubrick

11:20.388 --> 11:26.101
that most anything in his films
can't be regarded as arbitrary,

11:26.102 --> 11:29.149
that anything...
especially objects and colors

11:29.150 --> 11:33.027
and music and anything else,
probably have some intentional

11:33.028 --> 11:36.111
as well as
unintentional meaning to them.

11:36.112 --> 11:37.329
And so that struck me.

11:37.330 --> 11:39.072
Why a German typewriter?

11:39.073 --> 11:41.158
And in connection with that,

11:41.159 --> 11:47.039
I began to see the number 42
appear in the film.

11:47.040 --> 11:50.834
And for a German historian,
if you put the number 42

11:50.835 --> 11:53.088
and a German typewriter
together,

11:53.089 --> 11:54.463
you get the Holocaust,

11:54.464 --> 11:59.885
because it was in 1942
that the Nazis made the decision

11:59.886 --> 12:03.513
to go ahead and exterminate
all the Jews they could.

12:03.514 --> 12:07.267
And they did so in
a highly mechanical, industrial,

12:07.268 --> 12:09.728
and bureaucratic way.

12:09.729 --> 12:13.649
And so the juxtaposition
of the number 42

12:13.650 --> 12:16.574
and the typewriter was really
where it started for me

12:16.575 --> 12:19.988
in terms of the historical
content of the film.

12:19.989 --> 12:22.491
Of course "adler"
in German means "eagle."

12:22.492 --> 12:24.995
And eagle, of course,
is a symbol of Nazi Germany.

12:24.996 --> 12:27.290
It's also a symbol
of the United States.

12:27.291 --> 12:29.507
And Kubrick
generally has recourse to eagles

12:29.508 --> 12:31.297
to symbolize state power.

12:36.839 --> 12:40.217
Kubrick read Raul Hilberg's

12:40.218 --> 12:42.558
The Destruction
of the European Jews.

12:42.559 --> 12:44.897
And Hilberg's
major theme in there

12:44.898 --> 12:49.559
is that he focuses
on the apparatus of killing.

12:49.560 --> 12:52.154
And he emphasizes
how bureaucratic it was

12:52.155 --> 12:56.191
and how it was a matter
of lists and typewriters.

12:56.192 --> 12:58.819
Spielberg picked that up in
Schindler's List, of course.

12:58.820 --> 13:02.572
I mean, the film begins
with typewriters and lists

13:02.573 --> 13:04.700
and ends with a list,
of course.

13:04.701 --> 13:07.119
And so that informs...

13:07.120 --> 13:09.835
and I had a chance
to talk to Raul Hilberg.

13:09.836 --> 13:11.170
He visited Albion College.

13:11.171 --> 13:13.542
And he said that he and Kubrick
corresponded about this.

13:13.543 --> 13:16.672
And the fact that he read it
then, in the 1970s,

13:16.673 --> 13:19.049
when there was a big wave
of interest in Hitler

13:19.050 --> 13:22.342
and the Holocaust and the Nazis,
I think...

13:22.343 --> 13:25.387
I think just tells us
that that typewriter,

13:25.388 --> 13:27.014
that German typewriter...

13:27.015 --> 13:30.144
which by the way, changes color
in the course of the film,

13:30.145 --> 13:32.733
which typewriters
don't generally do...

13:32.734 --> 13:34.857
is terribly,
terribly important

13:34.858 --> 13:37.700
as a referent to that
particular historical event.

13:50.580 --> 13:54.124
- I worked in a film archive
for a decade,

13:54.125 --> 13:56.918
kind of like
fast-forwarding

13:56.919 --> 14:01.256
through World War II
ten times a day.

14:01.257 --> 14:03.008
But, you know, like,
when you see things

14:03.009 --> 14:04.676
over and over and again,

14:04.677 --> 14:06.553
their meanings change for you.

14:06.554 --> 14:14.853
Like, when you see these... see,
like, World War ll newsreels,

14:14.854 --> 14:17.606
like, after a while,
you come to realize

14:17.607 --> 14:20.400
that it's all faked on film.

14:20.401 --> 14:25.197
You are not seeing troops
storming Normandy.

14:25.198 --> 14:30.285
You're seeing troops
storming a beach in Hollywood.

14:30.286 --> 14:35.123
You know, like, you're not
seeing a plane flying to Japan.

14:35.124 --> 14:40.130
You're seeing a plane flying
over, you know, New Mexico.

14:42.298 --> 14:46.098
What you're really being shown
is, like, staged heroism.

14:46.099 --> 14:50.680
You know, like, you're seeing
men moving with machines,

14:50.681 --> 14:54.059
but you're not seeing what
they're talking about.

14:54.060 --> 14:57.781
And I think that that's
something that Kubrick plays on.

14:57.782 --> 15:02.901
Like, he plays on your
acceptance of visual infor...

15:02.902 --> 15:06.321
and also your ignorance
of visual information.

15:06.322 --> 15:10.742
Like he'll often, like,
put little special clues

15:10.743 --> 15:13.838
that you see,
like, in the corner.

15:17.291 --> 15:21.503
Every scene,
there's an impossibility,

15:21.504 --> 15:24.840
like the TV doesn't have a cord

15:24.841 --> 15:27.390
or even something as simple as,
like, them...

15:27.391 --> 15:30.846
they, like...
they bring too much luggage up.

15:30.847 --> 15:34.558
They, like... Jack, you know,
glances over at a pile

15:34.559 --> 15:36.027
of their luggage
that they brought,

15:36.028 --> 15:39.271
and ifs about the size
of a car.

15:39.272 --> 15:40.272
You know, a lot of it is jokes.

15:40.273 --> 15:43.191
Like, they're taking the tour.

15:43.192 --> 15:47.612
They're crossing the street
from the maze

15:47.613 --> 15:49.453
to go check out the garage.

15:49.454 --> 15:52.534
Like, a car
is just about to hit them.

15:52.535 --> 15:54.536
And then it cuts right before.

16:06.174 --> 16:08.842
- I had anticipated the film

16:08.843 --> 16:11.553
and had read
the Stephen King novel

16:11.554 --> 16:16.057
before the film came out and
found it a very appealing story.

16:16.058 --> 16:18.393
And I had spent
a lot of time

16:18.394 --> 16:23.231
at the Stanley Hotel
in Estes Park, Colorado,

16:23.232 --> 16:27.157
which is where he was inspired
to write the book The Shining.

16:27.158 --> 16:31.406
And so I, you know... I knew
a little bit of the background.

16:31.407 --> 16:33.246
And when
Kubrick's film came out,

16:33.247 --> 16:35.586
I was first in line to see it,
of course.

16:35.587 --> 16:38.872
And I was just
really disappointed

16:38.873 --> 16:40.999
and walked out of the theater

16:41.000 --> 16:43.674
wondering what the hell
I had just witnessed.

16:43.675 --> 16:50.675
And, I... actually,
my reverence for Stanley Kubrick

16:50.676 --> 16:52.678
diminished after that.

16:54.430 --> 16:58.600
I was disappointed, but I still
watched it every few years.

16:58.601 --> 17:02.105
I couldn't understand why I was
so attracted to watching a film

17:02.106 --> 17:04.105
that I actually didn't like.

17:04.106 --> 17:08.026
And now
in all these years later,

17:08.027 --> 17:11.613
I know why it is a great film.

17:11.614 --> 17:13.073
It is a masterpiece,

17:13.074 --> 17:15.667
but not for the reasons
that most people think.

17:19.829 --> 17:25.126
We are dealing with a guy
who has a 200 IQ.

17:25.127 --> 17:27.837
I believe
that when Stanley Kubrick

17:27.838 --> 17:33.343
finished with Barry Lyndon,
he was bored.

17:33.344 --> 17:36.846
He had conquered
the filmmaking landscape.

17:36.847 --> 17:41.518
He had succeeded in making
masterpiece after masterpiece,

17:41.519 --> 17:44.354
and he was bored.

17:44.355 --> 17:47.065
Barry Lyndon
is a boring movie.

17:47.066 --> 17:48.613
It is wonderfully shot.

17:48.614 --> 17:50.610
It is beautifully costumed.

17:50.611 --> 17:54.739
But it is a film
made by a guy who is bored.

17:54.740 --> 17:57.450
And I could see that.

17:57.451 --> 18:01.830
And so I think Stanley
retreated after Barry Lyndon.

18:01.831 --> 18:06.960
And he began working on
a new kind of film,

18:06.961 --> 18:11.214
a film that
had never been made before,

18:11.215 --> 18:14.509
a film that was made
by a bored genius

18:14.510 --> 18:21.099
who had thoroughly
emptied the jug of everything

18:21.100 --> 18:23.319
that could be done
in filmmaking.

18:23.320 --> 18:26.146
And he was looking
for the next thing.

18:26.147 --> 18:31.526
And what he did was he began
reading Subliminal Seduction

18:31.527 --> 18:34.952
and a number of other books
which were about how advertisers

18:34.953 --> 18:37.866
were injecting...

18:37.867 --> 18:40.827
injecting images,
subliminal images,

18:40.828 --> 18:44.581
into advertising
to sell products more.

18:44.582 --> 18:48.293
- Suggestible trends.

18:48.294 --> 18:51.218
- You know, there'll be
an ad for Gilbey's Gin,

18:51.219 --> 18:55.216
and inside, the ice cubes
will be various sex organs

18:55.217 --> 19:00.815
and things to add
a subliminal appeal to the ad.

19:03.434 --> 19:05.935
Kubrick went
to these advertisers,

19:05.936 --> 19:09.064
and he asked them
what their methods were.

19:09.065 --> 19:11.107
And then he took those methods

19:11.108 --> 19:15.153
and he applied them
to The Shining.

19:15.154 --> 19:19.574
Inside The Shining are
hundreds of subliminal images

19:19.575 --> 19:22.410
and shot line-ups.

19:22.411 --> 19:25.830
And what
these images are telling

19:25.831 --> 19:32.379
is an extremely disturbing
story about sexuality.

19:32.380 --> 19:36.549
And the subtext of the story,

19:36.550 --> 19:40.053
besides the other subtexts
of the story,

19:40.054 --> 19:46.559
is a story of haunted
phantoms and demons

19:46.560 --> 19:52.107
who are sexually attracted
to humans

19:52.108 --> 19:55.610
and are feeding off of them.

19:55.611 --> 20:00.490
You'd have to be able to be
a complete fanatic like I am

20:00.491 --> 20:02.117
in order to find all this,

20:02.118 --> 20:04.587
but, you know,
I'll give you my favorite.

20:04.588 --> 20:08.790
I'm only gonna give you one,
but I'll give you my favorite.

20:08.791 --> 20:12.669
When Jack meets
Stewart Ullman in the office

20:12.670 --> 20:14.798
at the very beginning
of the movie

20:14.799 --> 20:18.470
and he reaches over to shake
Jack Nicholson's hand...

20:18.471 --> 20:21.562
and so step through
that scene frame by frame.

20:21.563 --> 20:23.555
And the minute,
the moment,

20:23.556 --> 20:27.809
the frame that he
and Jack Nicholson touch hands

20:27.810 --> 20:31.479
and right after the line
that Barry Nelson says,

20:31.480 --> 20:34.649
which is, "Nice to see you,"

20:34.650 --> 20:41.030
you can see
that there's a paper...

20:41.031 --> 20:44.701
a paper tray on the desk.

20:44.702 --> 20:48.955
And as soon as they touch hands,
the paper tray

20:48.956 --> 20:53.543
turns into a very large
straight-on hard-on

20:53.544 --> 20:55.842
coming out of Barry nelson.

20:57.089 --> 20:59.048
Yeah, it's hilarious.

20:59.049 --> 21:04.012
It's a joke... a very serious
joke... but a joke by Stanley.

21:04.013 --> 21:06.723
And there's
many of these in the film.

21:06.724 --> 21:11.144
And very disturbing,
some of them.

21:11.145 --> 21:14.192
And this will all be in my film,
Kubrick the Magician.

21:14.193 --> 21:15.487
I'll give you one more.

21:15.488 --> 21:17.692
This one's harder to find, okay?

21:17.693 --> 21:20.365
And you have to know what
Stanley Kubrick looked like

21:20.366 --> 21:23.578
during the making of
The Shining to know this one.

21:23.579 --> 21:25.827
But if you go
to the opening credits

21:25.828 --> 21:27.660
and you pan the frame...

21:27.661 --> 21:30.246
you... you go through the frames,

21:30.247 --> 21:34.167
right after it says
"Directed by Stanley Kubrick,"

21:34.168 --> 21:38.880
as soon as his name
passes off the frame,

21:38.881 --> 21:44.511
stop and you will see that the
clouds have Stanley Kubrick

21:44.512 --> 21:49.390
airbrushed into them,
his face...

21:49.391 --> 21:52.732
with the beard and the wild hair
and the whole thing.

21:52.733 --> 21:54.774
I know this one's
a little harder to find.

21:54.775 --> 21:56.067
And I will have to...

21:56.068 --> 21:59.319
I will have to Photoshop
this one to show people it,

21:59.320 --> 22:03.198
